[normal]?” 
[normal]If it is a “no”, they do not want it, but if they will, regardless of the moral concerns of whether it is right to get it back, that is where they are pushing
[normal]. 
[normal]Richard Lloyd[bold]: This must be about giving people control over their finances, and the way to do that is to require the lenders to give you notice that they are going to use a CPA
[normal]. 
[normal]If they do not do that, you are not in control.
[normal]Peter Tutton[bold]: It is also about not pushing people further into difficulty
[normal]. 
[normal]Charging £75 to set up a repayment plan is not good, responsible lending
[normal]. 
[normal]It is taking someone who is clearly in financial difficulty and taking another fee out of them
[normal]. 
[normal]How can that be justifiable
[normal]? 
[normal]The thing with CPA is that we would expect lenders to start thinking, if CPA fails once, “Okay, why has that failed
[normal]? 
[normal]What should we do as a lender to try 
[normal]to
[normal] make sure, if this person is in financial difficult
[normal]y, we are not making it worse?”
[normal] rather than, “
[normal]I
[normal]f we have not heard from them, we will just take the money anyway and maybe we wil
[normal]l add some more charges.
[normal]”
