[normal]What difference will the new regulations make, in terms of making sure that affordability really is put front and centre?
[normal]Lesley Titcomb[bold]: You have come, really, to the crux of the proposals in our consultation paper, which are to ensure proper affordability checking and that loans are only made to those who can afford to repay them
[normal]. 
[normal]What we are looking at here is a package of measures to drive that
[normal]. 
[normal]There is obviously the proper assessment of affordability
[normal]—what are people’
[normal]s incomings, outgoings, etc.
[normal]—
[normal]but there are measures on top of that
[normal], such as
[normal] limiting the number o
[normal]f CPA attempts that can be made. The CPA
[normal] is
[normal],
[normal] in our view
[normal],
[normal] one of the incentives that drives firms not to carry out proper affordability assessments: they have no need to, because they know they can dip into a bank account to recover their money
[normal]. 
[normal]That is why you have to think of it as a proposal
[normal]. 
[normal]The key thing, from our point of view, is that we can make rules on this, whereas the OFT has only been able to make guidance underneath the principles that we have that people should be treating their customers fairly, anyway
[normal]. 
[normal]We are also able to devote more resources to monitori
[normal]ng against those rules, and taking
[normal] enforcement action where appropriate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q156 [bold]&#xa0; 
