[normal]              [bold]Q159 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Binley:[bold] Good morning, Minister
[normal]. 
[normal]The OFT found that 28 of the 40 lenders using continuous payment authority failed to explain how it operated, or that borrowers have the right to cancel
[normal]. 
[normal]Given this evidence, should the continuous
[normal] payment 
[normal]authority mechanism be stopped?
[normal]Jo Swinson[bold]: It obviously very much backs up, or is backed up by, the BIS research that we undertook 
[normal]as well in our consumer surveys;
[normal] what was supposed to be happening, in terms of information for consumers about CPA, was not happening
[normal]. 
[normal]As an initial step, I was very pleased to see the FCA getting the banks around the table to make it very clear, so that they understand that if a consumer rings the bank to cancel, then that is one way of doing it
[normal]. I 
[normal]think 
[normal]the continuous payment authority is at the crux of many of the problems within this market
[normal]. 
[normal]Lesley has already outlined the link to the issues of affordability, which has basically given many payday lenders much less of an incentive to be thorough in their affordability checks, because they have had that ability to dip into customers’ bank accounts and get paid first, almost like a preferred creditor
[normal]. 
[normal]I think that the proposal that the FCA have put forward is a very welcome one, because by limiting it to two CPA attempts over the course of the whole loan and it having to be the full amount of the loan that is requested, that rather removes the word “continuous” from “continuous payment authority
[normal]”. It is still a payment authority but
[normal] it is suddenly much more like a direct debit or a one-off payment, because the lender is then incentivised to make sure that they know 
[normal]that 
[normal]there will be 
[normal]enough 
[normal]to repay that when they take that payment
[normal]. 
[normal]When you couple that with the limits on rollovers, so that they cannot have a loan that is going on ad infinitum and building up interest charges, suddenly the business model that some payday lenders have been working on is very much changed indeed
[normal]. 
[normal]Obviously, the Competition Commission might ha
[normal]ve more to say on that business-
[normal]model point.
[normal] 
[normal]I think the CPA restrictions, as proposed, are incredibly welcome.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q160 [bold]&#xa0; 
